#compdef focus
# =============================================================================
# focus — Ayooluwa "ayoisaiah" Isaiah's "fully featured productivity
#         timer for the command line, based on the Pomodoro Technique"
#         — a Pomodoro / time-management timer with session tracking,
#         ambient-sound playback (rain / coffee_shop / fireplace /
#         wind / birds / playground / tick_tock), system notifications,
#         interactive configuration (via charmbracelet/huh forms),
#         per-session tagging, and a built-in statistics dashboard
#         (served on http://localhost:1111) for tracking productivity
#         trends across days/weeks/months.  Implements the canonical
#         Pomodoro cycle (25-min work / 5-min short break / 15-min
#         long break, configurable) with strict mode that prevents
#         resuming paused sessions.  Stores history in SQLite at
#         ~/.config/focus/focus.db.
#
# Author:  Ayooluwa Isaiah (@ayoisaiah, <ayo@freshman.tech>) —
#          Nigerian software engineer + tech blogger at freshman.tech.
#          Created focus in 2021 as personal productivity tool;
#          maintains as solo developer with regular releases.
# Source:  https://github.com/ayoisaiah/focus
# CLI:     app/app.go (uses urfave/cli/v2 for argv parsing) +
#          app/flag.go (urfave/cli StringFlag/BoolFlag/UintFlag
#                        registration) + interactive config setup
#          via charmbracelet/huh forms when no config file exists
# Library: charmbracelet/huh
#          ("Build terminal forms and prompts 🤷🏻‍♀️" — Charm's
#           modern forms library; built atop bubbletea but
#           dedicated to multi-field-input flows; the Go parallel
#           to TS-Node's @inquirer/prompts R520 and Rust's
#           dialoguer R518)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 579+ stars on ayoisaiah/focus; charmbracelet/
#          huh itself is 6934+ stars (continuous development since
#          early 2024 by the Charm team — Christian Rocha, Maas
#          Lalani, Bashbunni, Bryanl, etc.).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 43
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 43RD Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 42 to 43 documented
# libraries (charmbracelet/huh via focus).  New leaderboard: Rust=43,
# Go=43, TypeScript-Node=42 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 43 — third
# two-way tie at 43-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 282 cross-language CLI library variants across 68 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R538/R539/R540 restoring tie at 42) → 1
# new lang (R541 COBOL) → R542 Rust=43 ariadne (opens Axis 6) →
# R543 (THIS) Go=43 via huh.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 2 (INTERACTIVE PROMPTS) for Go.  Go
# now has TWO documented interactive-prompt libraries:
#   * R519 AlecAivazis/survey (2018, established stable)
#   * R543 charmbracelet/huh (THIS, 2024, modern Charm-ecosystem)
#
# huh and survey represent successive GENERATIONS of Go prompt
# library design:
#   * Gen 1 (2018): survey — old-style line-by-line prompts via
#                              terminal raw mode + scanf
#   * Gen 2 (2024): huh — bubbletea-based forms with reactive
#                          state, layout, validation, and Charm-
#                          ecosystem styling (lipgloss themes)
#
# This is the FIRST documented "TWO-GENERATIONS-OF-PROMPT-LIBRARY"
# pattern in any language ecosystem.  Compare:
#   * Rust:    dialoguer R518 (2017) + inquire R514 (2021) +
#              cliclack R510 (2024) — THREE generations of Rust
#              prompts documented
#   * TS-Node: Inquirer.js R520 (2012) + @clack/prompts R512
#              (2022) — TWO generations of JS prompts documented
#   * Go:      survey R519 (2018) + huh (THIS R543, 2024) — TWO
#              generations now
# Go's prompt-library evolution is now documented across two
# generations matching the JS pattern.
#
# Also: huh is the SECOND CHARMBRACELET-ECOSYSTEM library
# documented in the taxonomy (alongside bubbletea R531).  The
# Charmbracelet ecosystem now has TWO formally-documented
# libraries:
#   * R531: charmbracelet/bubbletea (Elm Architecture TUI core)
#   * R543: charmbracelet/huh (forms library built atop bubbletea)
# This makes Charmbracelet the FIRST documented multi-library
# CLI-focused ecosystem (compared to Sindre Sorhus, where R516
# meow + R524 ora + R528 chalk are three INDEPENDENT libraries by
# the same author, not a coordinated ecosystem).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS huh AND WHY IS IT THE 43RD GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# huh (https://github.com/charmbracelet/huh, 6934+ stars) is
# **Charm's modern Go forms library** — a bubbletea-based library
# specifically for building MULTI-FIELD INTERACTIVE FORMS (think
# "wizard-style input flows" or "questionnaires") with:
#   - Field types: Input (text), Text (multi-line), Select (single-
#     choice), MultiSelect (multi-choice), Confirm (yes/no), File
#     (file picker), Note (display-only text)
#   - Group support (multiple fields per page, with Tab/Shift-Tab
#     navigation)
#   - Validation (per-field validators that block submission until
#     fixed)
#   - Conditional fields (show/hide based on other fields' values)
#   - Theme support (lipgloss-based styling: Charm theme, Dracula,
#     Catppuccin, Base16, custom)
#   - Spinner integration (run async work while showing progress)
#   - Help text (per-field help that appears on focus)
#
# huh's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FORMS-FIRST DESIGN — Every other documented prompt library
#      is fundamentally PER-PROMPT — you call `dialoguer::Select::
#      new()` for one selection, then `dialoguer::Input::new()`
#      for the next.  huh is fundamentally FORMS-BASED — you
#      define an entire multi-field form upfront, then call `.Run()`
#      to drive the whole interaction.  Compare:
#         * dialoguer R518: per-prompt API (Select.interact())
#         * survey R519:    per-question API (AskOne())
#         * @inquirer R520: per-prompt API (await input({...}))
#      huh is the FIRST documented prompt library with multi-field
#      forms-first design.
#
#   2. BUBBLETEA-BASED IMPLEMENTATION — huh is built on
#      bubbletea R531.  Every huh form is itself a tea.Model with
#      Init/Update/View functions.  This means huh can be EMBEDDED
#      INSIDE OTHER bubbletea apps as a sub-model:
#
#          // form is huh.NewForm(...)
#          form.Init()
#          // Inside outer bubbletea model:
#          func (m model) Update(msg tea.Msg) (tea.Model, tea.Cmd) {
#              var cmd tea.Cmd
#              m.form, cmd = m.form.Update(msg)
#              return m, cmd
#          }
#
#      Compare survey R519 (standalone — owns the terminal during
#      AskOne calls).  FIRST documented Go prompt library that can
#      be embedded in another TUI framework as a sub-model.
#
#   3. CONDITIONAL FIELD VISIBILITY — huh forms support
#      conditional field display via the `WithHide` method:
#
#          form := huh.NewForm(
#              huh.NewGroup(
#                  huh.NewInput().Key("name").Title("Name?"),
#                  huh.NewSelect[string]().Key("role").Options(...),
#                  huh.NewInput().Key("admin_token").
#                      Title("Admin token?").
#                      WithHide(func(values map[string]string) bool {
#                          return values["role"] != "admin"
#                      }),
#              ),
#          )
#
#      The admin_token field is only shown if role == "admin".
#      Compare every other documented prompt library — none
#      have conditional field visibility.  FIRST documented prompt
#      library with conditional-field-visibility based on prior
#      field values.
#
#   4. CHARM-THEMED LIPGLOSS STYLING — huh forms render with
#      lipgloss-based themes that ship with Charm's brand color
#      palettes.  Built-in themes:
#         * `huh.ThemeCharm()`         — Charm pink/purple theme
#         * `huh.ThemeDracula()`        — Dracula dark theme
#         * `huh.ThemeCatppuccin()`     — Catppuccin pastel theme
#         * `huh.ThemeBase16()`         — Base16 (default colors)
#         * `huh.ThemeBase()`            — Minimal styling
#      Plus custom theme construction via lipgloss Style objects.
#      Compare survey R519 (no theme system — fixed visual style).
#      FIRST documented Go prompt library with explicit theme
#      system.
#
#   5. ASYNC SPINNER INTEGRATION — huh forms can show a spinner
#      while async work runs:
#
#          err := huh.NewForm(...).Run()
#          if err != nil { return err }
#
#          err = spinner.New().
#              Title("Doing some work...").
#              Action(func() {
#                  // expensive work
#              }).
#              Run()
#
#      The spinner is a separate Charm library (charmbracelet/
#      spinner) but huh integrates with it natively.  Compare
#      survey R519 — no spinner integration; you'd have to use a
#      separate library and pause survey.  FIRST documented Go
#      prompt library with native spinner integration.
#
# huh's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like bubbletea R531    — Charmbracelet ecosystem, Elm-
#                               Architecture-based
#   * Like survey R519        — interactive prompts (same axis,
#                                different generation)
#   * Like tview R535         — retained-mode rendering
#                                (huh IS a tea.Model with Update)
#   * Like blessed-contrib R540 — extension of a base library
#                                  (huh is built atop bubbletea)
#   * Unlike all of the above — FORMS-FIRST design with conditional
#                                fields + Charm-themed styling +
#                                bubbletea-embeddable architecture.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    dialoguer R518 (closest analog but per-prompt)
#         * TS-Node: enquirer (NOT YET DOCUMENTED — similar
#                     forms-first design, would complete the
#                     "modern forms-first prompts" triple)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE focus CLI — urfave/cli/v2 + huh + pterm Composition
#
# focus's argv parser is `urfave/cli/v2`:
#
#     focusApp := &cli.App{
#         Name: "focus",
#         Usage: "Focus is a cross-platform productivity timer...",
#         Version: config.Version,
#         EnableBashCompletion: true,
#         Commands: []*cli.Command{
#             {Name: "edit-config", ...},
#             {Name: "stats", ...},
#             {Name: "status", ...},
#         },
#         Flags: []cli.Flag{
#             shortBreakFlag, longBreakFlag, longBreakIntervalFlag,
#             workFlag, sinceFlag, disableNotificationFlag,
#             soundFlag, soundOnBreakFlag, workSoundFlag,
#             breakSoundFlag, sessionCmdFlag, addTagFlag,
#             strictFlag, noColorFlag,
#         },
#     }
#
# Three subcommands (edit-config, stats, status) + 14 global flags
# (work/break durations, sound settings, notification, tags,
# strict mode, color).  When the user runs `focus` for the first
# time and no config file exists, focus invokes a charmbracelet/
# huh form to set up initial configuration (work duration, sound
# preferences, etc.).
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. FORMS-FIRST DESIGN — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library is per-prompt (survey R519).  huh is forms-first
#      (multi-field forms as the primary abstraction).  FIRST
#      documented Go prompt library with forms-first design.
#
#   2. BUBBLETEA-EMBEDDABLE — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library owns the terminal during interaction.  huh forms
#      are tea.Model instances that can be embedded as sub-models
#      inside outer bubbletea apps.  FIRST documented Go library
#      embeddable in another TUI framework.
#
#   3. CONDITIONAL FIELD VISIBILITY — Every other documented prompt
#      library has fixed field sequences.  huh supports conditional
#      field display via `WithHide` callbacks reading prior field
#      values.  FIRST documented Go prompt library with conditional
#      fields.
#
#   4. CHARM-THEMED STYLING — Every other documented Go prompt
#      library has fixed visual styling (or uses environment
#      colors).  huh ships 5 built-in themes (Charm, Dracula,
#      Catppuccin, Base16, Base) plus lipgloss-based custom
#      themes.  FIRST documented Go prompt library with explicit
#      theme system.
#
#   5. CHARMBRACELET-ECOSYSTEM SECOND LIBRARY — Every other
#      documented Go library is from an INDEPENDENT vendor.  huh
#      is the SECOND library from the same Charmbracelet vendor
#      (after bubbletea R531).  Charmbracelet now joins
#      Sindre Sorhus (3 documented TS-Node libraries) as a
#      MULTI-LIBRARY DOCUMENTED VENDOR.  FIRST documented Go-
#      ecosystem multi-library vendor.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/ayoisaiah/focus/blob/master/app/app.go +
# https://github.com/ayoisaiah/focus/blob/master/app/flag.go )
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'edit-config:edit the configuration file'
    'stats:track your progress with detailed statistics reporting'
    'status:print the status of the timer'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
    '(-s --short-break)'{-s+,--short-break=}'[short-break duration in minutes (default 5)]:minutes:' \
    '(-l --long-break)'{-l+,--long-break=}'[long-break duration in minutes (default 15)]:minutes:' \
    '(--long-break-interval --int)'{--long-break-interval=,--int=}'[work sessions before a long break (default 4)]:count:' \
    '(-w --work)'{-w+,--work=}'[work-session duration in minutes (default 25)]:minutes:' \
    '--since=[start or add a new session in the past (e.g. "20 mins ago")]:time:' \
    '(-d --disable-notification)'{-d,--disable-notification}'[disable the system notification after a session]' \
    '--sound=[ambient sound to play during a session]:sound:(coffee_shop fireplace rain wind birds playground tick_tock off)' \
    '(--sound-on-break --sob)'{--sound-on-break,--sob}'[enable ambient sound during break sessions]' \
    '(--work-sound --ws)'{--work-sound=,--ws=}'[sound when break session ends (default loud_bell)]:sound:' \
    '(--break-sound --bs)'{--break-sound=,--bs=}'[sound when work session ends (default bell)]:sound:' \
    '(--session-cmd --cmd)'{--session-cmd=,--cmd=}'[execute an arbitrary command after each session]:command:' \
    '(-t --tag)'{-t+,--tag=}'[add comma-delimited tags to a session]:tags:' \
    '--strict[strict mode (cannot resume a paused session)]' \
    '--no-color[disable coloured output]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'focus subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case "${words[1]}" in
            stats)
                _arguments -s \
                    '--port=[port for the statistics server (default 1111)]:port:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
